  "published": "2025-06-10",
  "runtimeMin": 115,
  "format": "Sean, Amanda, and Chris pan the reshoot-scarred 'Ballerina' and dig into the Philippou brothers' bleak 'Bring Her Back,' then revisit 'Dogma' at 25. Kevin Smith takes the second half for an hour on the movie's Weinstein-era limbo and its re-release.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Ballerina'",
      "note": "the fifth John Wick film",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Ballerina",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Len Wiseman directs, Shay Hatton writes, Ana de Armas as Eve Macarro on a revenge spree through the Ruska Roma and a hidden village of killers. All three find it a mediocre script propped up by Chad Stahelski reshoots; the restaurant brawl is the high point, the tacked-on Keanu Reeves cameo and thin training arc the low ones. Gabriel Byrne, Norman Reedus, Ian McShane, Anjelica Huston, and Lance Reddick in his final role."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Bring Her Back'",
      "note": "the Philippou brothers' follow-up to 'Talk to Me'",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Bring Her Back",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Danny and Michael Philippou go grimmer than 'Talk to Me': Sally Hawkins as a bereaved foster mother trying to resurrect her drowned daughter, with two child performances from Sora Wong and Billy Barrett. Sean calls it well-made and genuinely upsetting - a grungy early-2000s horror mode, tooth violence and all. Amanda, warned off, sat it out (and a Zoom drop spared her the melon scene)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'Dogma' at 25",
      "note": "Sean, Amanda, and Chris revisit it",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Dogma",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "Back in theaters after years out of circulation. The hosts find it holds up: a silly action comedy about faith that's smarter than its shit-monster reputation, with Matt Damon and Ben Affleck as fallen angels, Linda Fiorentino, Alan Rickman, George Carlin, Chris Rock, Salma Hayek, and Alanis Morissette. Sean, raised Catholic, reads it as a mature film about the contradictions of the church."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "note": "the guest hosts for the hour",
      "guest": "Kevin Smith on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Dogma",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "Smith's hour-long account of the film's limbo: made at Miramax over Disney's objections, buried for two decades under Harvey Weinstein's rights, and finally freed when producer Alessandra Williams bought a tranche of Weinstein assets and re-released it on ~1,500 screens. It played Cannes Classics; Smith is writing a sequel."
        },
        {
          "title": "Clerks",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "The $30k debut, the second film ever sold at Sundance; Smith argues Miramax bought it to signal nothing had changed after the Disney sale."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mallrats",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "The Universal/Gramercy follow-up, before Smith set up an overall deal at Miramax."
        },
        {
          "title": "Chasing Amy",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "The first film under the Miramax overall deal; got a Criterion DVD."
        },
        {
          "title": "Red State",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "The Sundance self-distribution 'auction' stunt that birthed Smith's touring model - and the setting for the 'shut the fuck up' Weinstein anecdote."
        },
        {
          "title": "Clerks II",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "Made under the Weinstein Company; got an eight-minute ovation at Cannes in 2006, Smith's last visit before 'Dogma.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Zack and Miri Make a Porno",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "The last film Smith made with the Weinsteins before walking away."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tusk",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Smith owns the ending: he'll take the heat on it while still praising a film that also didn't know when to stop."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heretic",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "His last-great-thing pick - pop-culture philosophizing he calls 'porn for me' while writing the 'Dogma' sequel."
        },
        {
          "title": "Companion",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Also recommended; he praises Sophie Thatcher and calls it smart and original."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Substance",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Loved it - 'one of the bravest acts of cinema' - even as he notes it holds his beer on refusing to end."
        }
      ]
    }
